                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "A Feelings of Computing one.\n\nThis is the 2nd time I have returned to the idea of using inverse kinematics to manipulate graphics. But I have moved to plain SVG now, thinking that that is somewhat of a universal representation.\n\nAnd the new thing is reflecting on a reactive dataflow graph to discover parameterization automatically, and also extracting the params -> svg from the computational graph automatically, so the author only has to write parameterized SVG, and choose location of drag anchors, and the system can figure out how the anchors related to the SVG parameterization via numerical differentiation magically, so the drag handling is all free.\n\n"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "link",
                                "url": "https:\/\/tomlarkworthy.github.io\/lopebooks\/notebooks\/@tomlarkworthy_parameteric-svg.html"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "\n\nYou can get a lot of expressivity out of this for not much investment. You can choose how your parameters affect your SVG, it can  be quite weird. Not sure how to handle something like a normal drawing program though with multiple objects. I think I there is still something missing though. I generally want to make drawing diagrams easier, this is very finite dimensioned though."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
